# Claude Code Agent Instructions

You are working on a journaling and mood tracking web application built with Next.js 14, TypeScript, Supabase, OpenAI, and Stripe.

## Project Context
- **App Purpose**: Journaling + mood tracking with AI-generated reflections
- **Core Features**: Journal CRUD, mood logging, timeline view, AI insights (paid), search
- **User Limits**: Free tier (5 entries/day, 3 moods/day), AI features are paid only

## Technical Guidelines

### Code Patterns to Follow
- Use Next.js 14 App Router with server components by default
- Import using path mapping: `import { supabase } from '@/lib/supabase'`
- Style with Tailwind CSS utility classes
- TypeScript for all new files

### Architecture Rules
- Build on top of existing scaffold files in `project/` directory
- DO NOT recreate scaffold files unless fixing specific bugs
- Use established client configurations (Supabase, OpenAI, Stripe)

### Data Models to Implement
```typescript
User: { id, email }
Entry: { id, user_id, content, created_at }
MoodLog: { id, user_id, mood, created_at }
```

### Key Actions to Build
- **Entry**: createEntry, updateEntry, deleteEntry
- **Mood**: logMood
- **AI**: generateInsights (paid feature)
- **Search**: across entries and tags

### Pages to Implement
- `/dashboard` - Overview of recent entries and moods
- `/journal` - Entry management interface
- `/mood` - Mood tracking interface
- `/analytics` - AI insights and analytics (paid)
- `/settings` - User preferences and account settings

### Critical Requirements
- Implement user authentication with Supabase Auth
- Enforce rate limits (5 entries/day, 3 moods/day for free users)
- Gate AI features behind payment verification
- Ensure proper error handling and user feedback
- Implement search functionality across entries and tags
- Create timeline view combining entries and mood logs

When implementing features, prioritize user experience, data security, and proper integration with the existing tech stack.